[[File:External view of 198 Contemporary Arts and Learning, 2010.jpg|thumb|198 Contemporary Arts and Learning, 2010]] '''198 Contemporary Arts and Learning''', also known as the '''198 Gallery''' or '''198''', is an art space and gallery in [[Railton Road]], [[Brixton]], London.<ref name="De Souza2002">{{cite book|last1=De Souza|first1=Pauline|editor1-last=Donnell|editor1-first=Alison|title=Companion to Contemporary Black British Culture|date=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134700257|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VfdpdZ9DwH0C&lpg=PA1&dq=%22198%20Gallery%22&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=%22198%20Gallery%22&f=false|chapter=198 Gallery}}</ref>
The organisation, originally named Roots Community, was founded in 1988 by John 'Noel' Morgan and Zoe Lindsay-Thomas.<ref name="Davis2005">{{cite book|last1=Davis|first1=Lucy|last2=Bayode|first2=Folami|editor1-last=Atkinson|editor1-first=Dennis|editor2-last=Dash|editor2-first=Paul|title=Social and Critical Practice in Art Education|date=2005|publisher=Trentham Books|isbn=9781858563114|pages=81–90|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rOKmJsHYT0YC&lpg=PA82&dq=%22198%22%20railton%20road&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=%22198%22%20railton%20road&f=false|chapter=The 198 Gallery}}</ref> Lindsay-Thomas was a minicab driver and Morgan was manager of the Vargus Social Club in Landor Road. The organisation eventually changed its name to 198 Gallery, after its location on [[Railton Road]].
198's initial remit was to promote the work of contemporary African, Caribbean and Asian artists whose work represented the diversity of British society. 198 later expanded their policy to include artists from outside the UK.
==Exhibitions== During the course of its 28-year existence, 198 Contemporary Arts and learning has hosted projects and solo exhibitions showcasing the work of over four hundred British and international artists, including: [[Keith Piper (artist)|Keith Piper]], [[Eva Sajovic]],<ref>{{cite web|title=In/Visible Cities at 198 CAL - 19 November 2015|url=http://www.198.org.uk/node/253|website=198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|accessdate=21 August 2016|date=November 2015}}</ref> [[Hew Locke]], [[Brian Griffiths (artist)|Brian Griffiths]], Fernando Palma Rodriguez,<ref>{{cite web|title=Mechatronic Circus Schools Exhibition - 6 December 2000 to 16 June 2001|url=http://www.198.org.uk/artistic-programmes/archives/mechatronic-circus-schools-exhibition|website=198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> [[Quilla Constance]]<ref>{{cite web|title=PUKIJAM, Jennifer Allen aka Quilla Constance - 26 March 2015 to 8 May 2015|url=http://www.198.org.uk/artistic-programmes/upcoming-exhibition-4|website=198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> Barby Asante, [[Delaine Le Bas]],<ref>{{cite web|title=To Gypsyland, Delaine Le Bas - 21 June 2014 to 20 August 2014|url=http://www.198.org.uk/artistic-programmes/touring-exhibition|website=198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> and [[Godfried Donkor]] <ref>{{cite web|title= Social Impact Report 2015|url=http://www.198.org.uk/sites/default/files/Social%20Impact%20report%202015%202.pdf|website=198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|accessdate=22 August 2016}}</ref>
