[[File:Picou, Henri Pierre -Mark Antony and Cleopatra aboard an Egyptian barge - 1891.jpg|300px|thumb|right|A black-and-white print of ''Cléopâtre et Antoine sur le Cydnus''.]] '''Henri-Pierre Picou''' ([[Nantes]] 27 February 1824 &ndash; 17 July 1895) was a [[French people|French]] [[Painting|painter]].<ref name="Bryan">{{cite book |last = Bryan |first = Michael |title = Bryan's Dictionary of Painters and Engravers |volume = IV |publisher = The Macmillan Company |location = London |page = 115 |year = 1904 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cjEjAQAAIAAJ&pg=PP7#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref><ref name="harris">{{cite web |url=http://www.harrisantiques.com/Artist_Research_Biographies_Essay/FrenchPainters/Picou%20BIO.doc |title=Artist name |accessdate=26 June 2010 }}{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> His [[wikt:oeuvre|oeuvre]] began with portraits and classical historical subject matter but he later moved on to allegorical and mythological themes.<ref name="vapereau">{{cite book |last = Vapereau |first = Gustave |title = Dictionnaire universel des contemporains: contenant toutes les personnes notables de la France et des pays étrangers |publisher = Librairie Hachette |location = Paris |pages = 1249–1250 |year = 1893 |edition = Sixième |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfkMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |language=fr}}</ref>
He was an [[academic painter]] and one of the founders of the [[Neo-Grec]] school, along with his close friends [[Gustave Boulanger]], [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]], and [[Jean-Louis Hamon]], also academic painters. All of them studied in the workshops of both [[Hippolyte Delaroche|Paul Delaroche]] and later [[Marc-Charles-Gabriel Gleyre|Charles Gleyre]]. Picou's style was noticeably influenced by Gleyre. While the rest of the group generally painted classical and mythological subjects, Picou also received commissions for large religious frescoes from many churches, including the [[Église Saint-Roch]].<ref name="safran">{{cite web |url= http://www.safran-arts.com/42day/art/art4jul/art0717.html |title= ART / 4 / 2DAY |accessdate= 26 June 2010 }}</ref>
[[File:Picou, Henri Pierre - Allegory of Spring - 1871.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Picou's ''Allegory of Spring'', painted in 1871, now housed at the [[Museo Nazionale del Bargello]].]] His artistic debut was at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] in 1847. The next year he was awarded a second-class medal for his painting, ''Cléopâtre et Antoine sur le Cydnus''. Also known as ''Cleopatra on the Cydnus'', it is commonly regarded as Picou's masterpiece. This showing at the Salon in 1848 was written about by the critic [[Théophile Gautier]], who felt that the subject matter was too ambitious, but also said that "As it is, it gives the best hope for the future of the young artist, and ranks among the seven or eight most important paintings of the Salon."<ref>{{cite book |last = Gautier |first = Théophile |title = Salon de 1848 |publisher = [[La Presse (French newspaper)|La Presse]] |date = April 1848 |quote = Tel qu'il est, il donne les meilleures espérances pour l'avenir du jeune artiste, et se classe parmi les sept ou huit toiles les plus importantes du Salon. |url=http://classiques.uqac.ca/classiques/gautier_theophile/Salon_de_1848/Salon_de_1848.html |language=fr}}</ref> In 1875, the painting was exhibited in New York, and afterward found lodgment on the walls of a [[art museum|private art gallery]] in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite book |last = Shepp |first = Daniel B. |title = Shepp's library of history and art: a pictorial history of all lands and times; the great incidents of history set forth by the magic pencils of the world's greatest artists |publisher = Globe Bible Publishing Company |location = Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |page = 118 |year = 1905 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vuPTAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> [[File:Picou, Henri Pierre - La Pêche miraculeuse - 19th century.jpg|thumb|La Pêche miraculeuse]] Picou maintained a large workshop in Paris on the [[Boulevard de Magenta]], which provided him room to work on his expansive frescoes. His popularity continued to rise and he went on to win the Second [[Prix de Rome]] in 1853 for his painting, ''Jésus chassant les vendeurs du Temple'' (''The Moneylenders Chased from the Temple''), and another second-class medal for his Salon painting in 1857. From his debut in 1847, he was a regular at the Salon, showing almost every year until his final exhibit in 1893.<ref name="vapereau" /><ref>{{cite book |last = Bellier de la Chavignerie |first = Emile |last2 = Auvray |first2 = Louis |title = Dictionnaire général des artistes de l'école française depuis l'origine des arts du dessin jusqu'à nos jours: architectes, peintres, sculpteurs, graveurs et lithographes |publisher = Librairie Renouard |location = Paris |page = 267 |year = 1885 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_wUrAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false |language=fr}}</ref> He has been called the most fashionable painter towards the close of the [[Second French Empire]].<ref name="Bryan" />
