{{Infobox person | name = Maryam Yakubova | birth_date = October 9, 1929 | death_date = February 2, 1987 }}
'''Maryam Yakubova''' ({{lang-uz|'''Maryam Yoqubova'''}}) (October 9, 1929 - February 2, 1987) was an [[Uzbekistan]]i stage and film actress of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] era.
Yakubova was born in [[Bukhara]], the daughter of a worker in a cotton factory. In her childhood she lived in the household of the [[emir of Bukhara]]. Early in life she was forced into an [[arranged marriage]],<ref name="bukharianjewishcongress.org">{{cite web|url=http://bukharianjewishcongress.org/theater/680-maryam-yakubov-greatest-happiness-recognition-of-audience|title=Марьям Якубова: "Я познала величайшее счастье - признание и любовь зрителей|website=bukharianjewishcongress.org|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> but soon she escaped and traveled to [[Moscow]] to study, graduating in 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mytashkent.uz/2011/07/19/kak-ya-stala-aktrisoj/|title=«Как я стала актрисой»|date=19 July 2011|publisher=mytashkent.uz|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> Returning home, she began a career as a stage actress.<ref name="bukharianjewishcongress.org"/> She also began to work in film, her first role in the medium coming in 1925.<ref name="Якубоваkino">{{cite web|url=http://www.uzbekkino-ussr.asia/maryam-yakubova.html|title=Марьям Якубова|website=www.uzbekkino-ussr.asia|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> During [[World War II]] she performed for soldiers at the front with other artists from the [[Uzbek SSR]]. She continued her film career, working with [[Tajikistan]]i and Uzbekistani directors. She also appeared often on radio,<ref name="bukharianjewishcongress.org"/> and made many appearances on television as well.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | year = 2000–2005 | title = Maryam Yoqubova | encyclopedia = National Encyclopedia of Uzbekistan | publisher = National Encyclopedia of Uzbekistan State Scientific Publishing House | location = Tashkent | language = Uzbek | id =}}</ref> For her work, Yakubova was awarded the title of [[People's Artist of Uzbekistan]];<ref name="bukharianjewishcongress.org"/> during her career she also received the [[Order of the Badge of Honour]], as well as numerous medals, diplomas, and other awards.<ref name="Якубоваkino"/> She died in Tashkent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kino-teatr.ru/teatr/acter/w/sov/36847/bio/|title=Марьям Якубова|website=Кино-Театр.РУ|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>
